Exercise 1: Change Background Color

HTML:

html
Copy code
<button id="changeColorButton">Change Color</button>
JavaScript:

javascript
Copy code
var changeColorButton = document.getElementById("changeColorButton");

changeColorButton.addEventListener("click", function() {
  var randomColor = generateRandomColor();
  document.body.style.backgroundColor = randomColor;
});

function generateRandomColor() {
  var letters = "0123456789ABCDEF";
  var color = "#";
  for (var i = 0; i < 6; i++) {
    color += letters[Math.floor(Math.random() * 16)];
  }
  return color;
}
Explanation:

We first select the button element with the id "changeColorButton" using getElementById.
We add an event listener to the button, which listens for a "click" event.
Inside the event listener, we call the generateRandomColor function to generate a random color.
We then set the background color of the body element to the generated random color using document.body.style.backgroundColor.
Exercise 2: Image Slider

HTML:

html
Copy code
<div id="slider">
  <img src="image1.jpg" alt="Image 1" />
  <img src="image2.jpg" alt="Image 2" />
  <img src="image3.jpg" alt="Image 3" />
</div>
<button id="prevButton">Previous</button>
<button id="nextButton">Next</button>
JavaScript:

javascript
Copy code
var slider = document.getElementById("slider");
var prevButton = document.getElementById("prevButton");
var nextButton = document.getElementById("nextButton");
var currentIndex = 0;

prevButton.addEventListener("click", function() {
  if (currentIndex > 0) {
    currentIndex--;
  } else {
    currentIndex = slider.children.length - 1;
  }
  showImage(currentIndex);
});

nextButton.addEventListener("click", function() {
  if (currentIndex < slider.children.length - 1) {
    currentIndex++;
  } else {
    currentIndex = 0;
  }
  showImage(currentIndex);
});

function showImage(index) {
  for (var i = 0; i < slider.children.length; i++) {
    slider.children[i].style.display = "none";
  }
  slider.children[index].style.display = "block";
}
Explanation:

We select the slider container, previous button, and next button using getElementById.
We set an initial index variable (currentIndex) to keep track of the currently displayed image.
We add event listeners to the previous and next buttons to handle their click events.
Inside the event listeners, we update the currentIndex based on the button clicked.
We call the showImage function, passing the updated currentIndex, to display the corresponding image.
The showImage function hides all images by setting their display CSS property to "none" and displays the image at the given index by setting its display CSS property to "block".
Note: Make sure to replace "image1.jpg", "image2.jpg", "image3.jpg" with the actual paths to your images.

These are just a couple of examples with explanations. The other exercises can be implemented in a similar manner. They involve manipulating the DOM elements, handling events, and implementing specific functionalities using JavaScript. Feel free to ask if you have any specific questions or need further clarification!
